Exactly ‚Äî you‚Äôve interpreted that perfectly, and this distinction is the core of the problem.

Let‚Äôs unpack it precisely in securitisation terms, and why it‚Äôs not senior-commensurate even though ‚Äúissuer senior fees‚Äù normally sit above interest.

‚∏ª

1Ô∏è‚É£ What is normal in a securitisation waterfall

In a true-sale securitisation, you have:
	‚Ä¢	Issuer-level taxes, trustee, agent and servicing fees ranking senior to note interest ‚Äî this is standard and rating-agency-driven.
	‚Ä¢	These are transaction expenses, incurred by the SPV/issuer, and are tightly defined and capped (e.g. ‚ÄúSenior Expenses‚Äù or ‚ÄúIssuer Senior Costs‚Äù).
	‚Ä¢	Crucially, they are not operating expenses of the originator/servicer, nor any third-party tax liabilities of the seller.

That hierarchy is fine because investors understand they are paying to keep the structure functioning (administration, trustees, hedge, etc.) ‚Äî not subsidising the operating company.

‚∏ª

2Ô∏è‚É£ What‚Äôs happening in the Auto1 Inventory Facility

Here, the priority of payments at the CarCo level reads:

‚ÄúFirst, to unpaid Taxes due and payable by CarCo ‚Ä¶
Second, to CarCo Agent Fees ‚Ä¶
Fourth, amounts to be transferred to the Issuer ‚Ä¶‚Äù   Ôøº

That means:
	‚Ä¢	The waterfall pays CarCo‚Äôs own taxes (VAT, trade tax, corporate-level obligations) and its internal agent fees before remitting anything to the Issuer.
	‚Ä¢	The Issuer waterfall then begins with its own senior expenses and senior interest.

So, effectively, there‚Äôs a double layer of seniority ‚Äî but the top layer benefits CarCo as operating borrower, not the SPV or noteholders.

‚∏ª

3Ô∏è‚É£ Why this is non-senior-commensurate
	‚Ä¢	These CarCo taxes are not issuer or trust-level taxes; they‚Äôre corporate liabilities of the borrower.
	‚Ä¢	They rank structurally senior to the lender‚Äôs (Issuer‚Äôs) claims on collections ‚Äî even though, economically, they belong beneath debt service.
	‚Ä¢	Worse, if CarCo‚Äôs cash is tight, those taxes can consume liquidity that should flow up to pay Senior Note interest.
	‚Ä¢	The structure even allows Issuer reserves (Trade-Tax Reserve or Senior Reserve) to be used to backfill those CarCo tax payments  Ôøº ‚Äî meaning senior liquidity can be diverted to a borrower‚Äôs statutory obligations.

That‚Äôs a fundamental inversion of the securitisation principle:
the cash waterfall should serve the funding structure first, not the borrower‚Äôs ongoing business overheads.

‚∏ª

4Ô∏è‚É£ Why it‚Äôs not just semantics

Rating agencies tolerate ‚ÄúIssuer Senior Expenses‚Äù because they‚Äôre predictable and ring-fenced.
Here, CarCo‚Äôs taxes are variable, operational, and outside the structure‚Äôs control ‚Äî a leakage risk, not a structural necessity.
If CarCo under-remits VAT or faces a tax dispute, the waterfall forces noteholder cash to cure that first, turning the lender into an involuntary tax guarantor.

‚∏ª

5Ô∏è‚É£ How to fix it (what a senior lender would demand)
	‚Ä¢	Reclassify CarCo taxes and agent fees as CarCo Operating Costs, subordinate to any payment to the Issuer (i.e. below debt service).
	‚Ä¢	Retain only issuer-related costs (trustee, agent, account bank, rating, hedge, etc.) in the senior expense bucket.
	‚Ä¢	If tax pre-funding is required for VAT, create a dedicated VAT Reserve funded day-one, segregated and sized to expected obligations, with clear top-up logic ‚Äî not waterfall priority.
	‚Ä¢	Prohibit use of Senior or Trade-Tax Reserve for any borrower-level tax items.

‚∏ª

‚úÖ In short:
Yes ‚Äî the weakness isn‚Äôt that ‚Äúfees and taxes‚Äù are above interest per se (that‚Äôs normal at SPV level).
The weakness is that here, they‚Äôre CarCo‚Äôs own taxes and fees, and the structure explicitly allows them to be paid ‚Äî and even topped-up by Issuer liquidity ‚Äî ahead of the lender‚Äôs claims.
That‚Äôs a borrower-side leakage, inconsistent with a senior secured or securitised position.

Both S&P and Scope explicitly described how they took comfort with the structural and operational weaknesses you noted ‚Äî mainly the CarCo-level fees/taxes, AUTO1 dependency, and commingling/operational complexity ‚Äî through layered mitigants:

‚∏ª

üîπ 1. AUTO1 Recourse & Liquidity Reserves
	‚Ä¢	Scope ¬ß4.4.4 and S&P p. 4‚Äì5: AUTO1 (the corporate parent) is contractually obliged, while solvent, to cover any shortfalls on senior expenses, note interest, and negative trading margin via the intercompany loan to CarCo NL.
‚Üí This recourse was central to both agencies‚Äô comfort that taxes and other CarCo-level senior costs wouldn‚Äôt erode note protection.
(Source: Scope p. 13 ‚Äì ‚ÄúAUTO1 will cover any shortfalls‚Ä¶ via intercompany loan‚Ä¶ If AUTO1 cannot, early amortisation follows.‚Äù  Ôøº)
	‚Ä¢	Liquidity reserves:
	‚Ä¢	Senior reserve ‚âà six months of senior interest + fees coverage.
	‚Ä¢	Mezzanine reserve ‚âà four months of mezz interest.
	‚Ä¢	Both funded from junior proceeds and dynamically maintained.
(Scope ¬ß 4.4.3  Ôøº)
‚Üí S&P validated the same mitigant, modelling 12-month sale-delay and 12% Euribor stress; CE deemed sufficient  Ôøº.

‚∏ª

üîπ 2. Tax-Reserve Comfort
	‚Ä¢	Scope (¬ß 4.4.3.3‚Äì4): ‚ÄúVAT tax reserve‚Äù + ‚ÄúTrade tax reserve‚Äù funded by junior proceeds pre-emptively cover CarCo VAT and non-deductible trade-tax risk  Ôøº.
	‚Ä¢	S&P mirrored: ‚Äúpresence of respective reserves mitigates trade-tax, VAT and dilution risks‚Äù  Ôøº.
‚Üí Hence, while taxes sit at CarCo level, the funded reserves isolate these exposures from senior note performance.

‚∏ª

üîπ 3. Operational / Commingling Risk
	‚Ä¢	Both agencies classified operational risk as high, capping the rating at ‚ÄòA‚Äô absent AUTO1 solvency or BUS activation.
(S&P p. 3 ‚Äì ‚Äúmax potential rating ‚ÄòA‚Äô due to operational risk‚Ä¶ uplift limited to 3 notches‚Äù  Ôøº; Scope p. 18‚Äì22  Ôøº)
	‚Ä¢	Mitigants accepted:
	‚Ä¢	‚ÄúHot‚Äù back-up servicer (Autorola GmbH) ready within 10 days.
	‚Ä¢	Daily cash sweeps from AUTO1 accounts into CarCo/issuer accounts.
	‚Ä¢	Liquidity reserves to bridge a disruption period.

‚∏ª

üîπ 4. Structural / Legal Complexity
	‚Ä¢	Scope ¬ß 6 and ¬ß 7: complexity from nine jurisdictions acknowledged, but comfort taken from pledges over assets and collection accounts to the Security Trustee  Ôøº.
	‚Ä¢	S&P: confirmed bankruptcy remoteness and true-sale opinions  Ôøº.

‚∏ª

üîπ 5. Market-Value & Re-purchase Risk
	‚Ä¢	S&P quantified MVD stress (AAA 27%, A 15%, BB 4.5%) and required dynamic CE floors (20% senior / 10% mezz)  Ôøº.
	‚Ä¢	Scope likewise modelled AUTO1 default timing and liquidation proceeds, assuming reserves pay senior interest during unwind  Ôøº.

‚∏ª

üîπ 6. Why Ratings Still ‚ÄúComfortable‚Äù

Despite the non-standard CarCo layer and AUTO1 dependency, agencies judged:
	‚Ä¢	AUTO1‚Äôs corporate strength + recourse + reserves = sufficient to support ‚ÄúA(sf)‚Äù senior note rating.
	‚Ä¢	The senior tranche‚Äôs liquidity and subordination absorbed residual tax, operational, and FX risks.
	‚Ä¢	Ratings were explicitly capped by operational exposure, not by collateral quality or legal risk.

‚∏ª

In short:
Yes, the tax and expense items arise at CarCo level rather than borrower-issuer, but the agencies relied on the AUTO1 recourse undertaking and pre-funded tax/liquidity reserves to bridge that weakness, while explicitly capping the achievable senior rating due to operational and structural complexity.

Excellent and very pertinent questions ‚Äî this goes to the heart of how private, asset-based warehouse facilities like Auto1‚Äôs can be presented to your internal credit committee without relying on ‚Äúsoft‚Äù corporate recourse that would never survive a real enforcement.

Let‚Äôs unpack this in layers: (i) how to frame it internally, (ii) what due diligence and legal questions to ask counsel, and (iii) what‚Äôs typically acceptable (and what isn‚Äôt) for a true senior secured position.

‚∏ª

üß© 1Ô∏è‚É£ Framing the internal credit rationale

Your goal is to show that credit protection relies on self-liquidating collateral and structural mechanics, not on the solvency or goodwill of Auto1.

Here‚Äôs the logic chain you should use internally:

Topic	How to frame it for Credit
Nature of ‚Äúrecourse‚Äù	The so-called recourse to Auto1 is not a legally enforceable guarantee but a conditional intra-group loan arrangement. Auto1 can stop funding if insolvent. Hence, we assume no reliance on Auto1 credit in our base case or stress case.
Risk focus	The facility is underwritten on collateral performance and structural liquidity (inventory liquidation proceeds, reserves, advance-rate haircuts, and early amortisation triggers).
Agency precedent	Rating agencies modelled the recourse only as a temporary liquidity mitigant, capping the achievable rating at A(sf) to reflect operational/servicer dependence. We align with that view ‚Äî no corporate support uplift.
Internal risk assumption	Treat Auto1 as servicer/operator, not guarantor. We require that all cash sweeps, account controls, reserves, and eligibility mechanics work even if Auto1 stops injecting liquidity.
Downside scenario	Upon Auto1 distress: revolving period ends, pool stops replenishing, collateral is liquidated, and reserves cover timing gaps. Hence, structural protection, not recourse, drives recovery.

That phrasing makes it clear you are not giving credit to the corporate, aligning your stance with conservative structured-credit doctrine.

‚∏ª

‚öñÔ∏è 2Ô∏è‚É£ Questions to raise with external counsel

You want counsel to confirm that the structure legally functions without Auto1 solvency support and that any ‚Äúrecourse‚Äù language is non-reliant. Here are the questions grouped by theme:

üî∏ A. Legal enforceability and separability
	1.	Is there any legally binding guarantee or payment undertaking from Auto1 SE (the parent)?
‚Äì If yes, is it unconditional and continuing, or subject to solvency / corporate-benefit tests?
‚Äì If not, confirm explicitly in their opinion that no recourse exists to Auto1 for the Issuer or Noteholders.
	2.	Can CarCo perform all payment obligations to the Issuer without Auto1 intra-group funding?
‚Äì If Auto1 ceases intercompany advances, does that itself trigger an Event of Default or Early Amortisation Event?
	3.	Is the intercompany loan subordinated or structurally senior to the Issuer‚Äôs security?
‚Äì Ensure Auto1 has no claim ahead of secured lenders in CarCo insolvency.

üî∏ B. Bankruptcy remoteness and claw-back
	4.	Would any intercompany loan or repayment from CarCo to Auto1 be subject to claw-back or set-off in Auto1 insolvency?
‚Äì You want assurance that no upstream exposure to Auto1‚Äôs estate can contaminate CarCo.
	5.	Does the legal true-sale or pledge structure remain enforceable if Auto1 enters insolvency in Germany?
‚Äì Confirm with German counsel that any Insolvenzverwalter cannot treat CarCo as part of Auto1‚Äôs consolidated estate.

üî∏ C. Operational continuity
	6.	Who controls the accounts and collections post-Auto1 default?
‚Äì Is there a contractual step-in or security-trust arrangement giving the Security Trustee/Issuer immediate control?
	7.	What rights does the Servicer (Auto1) lose upon default or insolvency?
‚Äì How quickly can a back-up servicer be appointed and collections redirected?

üî∏ D. Disclosure / Representation risk
	8.	How is the ‚Äúrecourse‚Äù described in the legal documentation?
‚Äì Ensure there is no misleading reference suggesting investors rely on Auto1 credit (this is critical for internal sign-off and future distribution).

‚∏ª

üßÆ 3Ô∏è‚É£ How to position this as acceptable for a senior secured lender

This can be acceptable if and only if the following are demonstrably true:

Condition	Explanation
Structural self-liquidity	Reserve accounts (Senior, VAT, Trade-Tax) + overcollateralisation can cover 3‚Äì6 months of senior interest while collateral is liquidated.
Early-am triggers	Immediate switch to amortisation upon Auto1 default or failure to fund intercompany advances.
Collateral control	Security Trustee has perfected pledges over all inventory, accounts, and proceeds in enforceable jurisdictions (NL, DE, etc.).
No Auto1 dependency for servicing post-default	A contracted ‚Äúhot‚Äù back-up servicer (Autorola or similar) can take over within days.
Legal opinions	Confirm bankruptcy remoteness of CarCo, enforceability of pledges, and non-reliance on Auto1 solvency.

If those are all satisfied, you can justify to credit that:

‚ÄúWhile the facility includes an intra-group liquidity mechanism from Auto1, the transaction is structured to survive a cessation of that support. We underwrite to collateral and structural CE only; Auto1 support is treated as a contingent buffer, not as credit enhancement.‚Äù

‚∏ª

üß† 4Ô∏è‚É£ Internally, your risk narrative should sound like this:

‚ÄúWe treat Auto1 as a servicer, not a credit backstop.
The legal structure isolates the financed inventory and sale proceeds in a bankruptcy-remote CarCo.
Auto1‚Äôs intra-group loan exists only to smooth liquidity; if withdrawn, the structure delevers through early amortisation, supported by funded reserves and asset sales.
Therefore, our credit decision relies solely on asset-level recoveries and structural features ‚Äî not on Auto1‚Äôs balance sheet.‚Äù

‚∏ª

üîç 5Ô∏è‚É£ Bottom line on acceptability

‚úÖ Acceptable for senior structured exposure if:
	‚Ä¢	Auto1‚Äôs intercompany loan is purely operational, not a dependency.
	‚Ä¢	Early-am triggers are tight.
	‚Ä¢	CarCo and Issuer are bankruptcy-remote and cash-controlled.
	‚Ä¢	You get explicit legal comfort on non-recourse.

‚ùå Not acceptable if:
	‚Ä¢	Cash waterfalls or reserve mechanics implicitly rely on Auto1 cash injections to meet senior obligations.
	‚Ä¢	Legal opinions can‚Äôt clearly state that investors have no enforceable claim against Auto1.
	‚Ä¢	There‚Äôs no robust back-up servicing or post-default account control.

‚∏ª

